Underwater Shock Wave Visualization and Analysis (70 items，7.0%) slope=0.11%/yr

The Shock Wave Symposium covered a wide range of topics including shock wave generation in various mediums, underwater explosion phenomena, shock wave focusing, microbubble dynamics, and shock wave interactions with different materials. The research presented focused on experimental studies, theoretical analyses, and future prospects in the field of shock wave physics. The symposium aimed to explore diverse aspects of shock wave behavior, from underwater shock waves induced by metal rods to shock wave generation in laser-produced plasmas, providing insights into the complex dynamics of these phenomena in different environments.

Shock Wave Propagation Analysis with Numerical Methods (66 items，6.6%) slope=-0.40%/yr

The consultation covered a wide range of topics related to shock tube experiments, including shock wave angles, overpressure distribution, shock wave interaction, shock structures, nozzle shape optimization, and turbulence analysis. Participants delved into numerical simulations, boundary layer flow instabilities, chemical reactions, dissipation in fluid models, and heat transport calculations. The discussions also touched on shock wave noise scaling, vortex interactions, particle diffusion, and shock wave visualization techniques. The consultation showcased a diverse array of research interests and methodologies within the field of shock tube experimentation.

Detonation Modeling and Analysis (55 items，5.5%) slope=0.16%/yr

The consultation covered a wide range of topics related to explosive phenomena, including detonation wave analysis, propulsion methods, explosive deformation, and reactivity effects. Participants delved into numerical simulations, equation of state development, and blast wave characteristics. The discussions also touched on specific applications like laser propulsion, gas detonation generators, and detonation wave propagation in various mixtures. Overall, the consultation showcased a diverse set of research interests and technical approaches within the field of explosive dynamics.

Hypersonic Flow Simulation and Analysis (55 items，5.5%) slope=0.53%/yr

The consultation covered a wide range of topics in hypersonics, including boundary layer transport, shock wave generation, aerodynamic characteristics, turbulence modeling, MHD flow control, and numerical simulations. Participants delved into specific areas like boundary layer flow instabilities, wake analysis, projectile interactions, and real gas modeling challenges. The discussions also touched on deep learning applications, transient ballistics, two-phase flow observations, and shock-induced combustion analysis in hypersonic environments. Overall, the consultation showcased a diverse set of research interests and technical challenges in the field of hypersonics.

Blast Wave Phenomena Analysis (50 items，5.0%) slope=0.34%/yr

The consultation covered a wide range of topics related to explosives and blast mitigation, including safety assessments, shock wave interactions, pressure measurements, and blast wave effects in various scenarios. Participants discussed experimental studies, numerical analyses, and technological developments aimed at understanding and reducing the impact of explosions. Key areas of focus included evaluating explosive properties, blast wave mitigation strategies, and the effects of different materials and designs on pressure wave propagation. The discussions highlighted the importance of research in enhancing safety measures and developing technologies to minimize blast injuries and damage.

The research aims to improve measurement accuracy, resolution, and detection methods across various experimental setups and conditions, highlighting the complexity and importance of studying shock waves in different contexts.

High-Speed Flow Control and Interaction Analysis (41 items，4.1%) slope=0.30%/yr

Participants delved into detailed analyses of phenomena like wave-particle interactions, shock waves, and nozzle geometry's influence on gas mixing efficiency. The research areas span from scramjet engine intakes to high-pressure water industry nozzles, showcasing a diverse exploration of cutting-edge topics in the field.

Key areas of interest included density field measurements, aerodynamic heating tests, magnetohydrodynamic properties of plasma, and simulations of Mars atmospheric entry environments. The studies aimed to enhance understanding and develop techniques for improving spacecraft performance and safety during re-entry and Mars missions.

Porous Media Interaction with Shock Waves (41 items，4.1%) slope=-0.05%/yr

The consultation covered a wide range of topics related to shock wave interactions, including shock wave modulation, reduction, generation, and propagation in various mediums and conditions. Participants discussed shock wave mitigation strategies such as porous media interaction, 'Magic Fence,' and multilayer mesh media interference. The impact of factors like flow conditions, material properties, and external fields on shock wave behavior was also highlighted. Overall, the discussions delved into both experimental and analytical investigations of shock wave phenomena in diverse scenarios, emphasizing the complexity and importance of understanding these interactions for various applications.

Detonation Transition Analysis in Confined Channels (39 items，3.9%) slope=0.23%/yr

The consultation covered a wide range of topics related to detonation and deflagration phenomena, including DDT, flame acceleration, shock wave effects, and fluid transport in various configurations. Participants discussed experimental studies, numerical analyses, and visualization techniques to understand detonation behavior, propagation characteristics, and transition processes. The focus was on areas such as deflagration-to-detonation transition suppression, detonation initiation, shock wave interactions, and flow field evaluations in different combustion and propulsion systems. The discussions highlighted the complexity of these phenomena and the importance of research in enhancing safety and efficiency in related engineering applications.

Laser-Induced Shock Wave Dynamics (38 items，3.8%) slope=-0.32%/yr

The consultation covered a wide range of topics related to laser-induced shock waves, microbubbles, cavitation, and stress wave formation. Key areas of interest included femtosecond laser-induced micro-shock waves, bubble dynamics analysis, cavitation bubble generation and disappearance, and high-speed observation of cell morphology post-shock wave irradiation. The research also delved into pressure characteristics of laser-induced shock waves, residual snow stress field formation, and the impact of acoustic impedance matching on blast wave collision. Additionally, studies focused on optical wave propagation in deep tissue and the visualization of various bubble-attached structures.

High-Speed Flow Visualization and Measurement (36 items，3.6%) slope=0.24%/yr

The consultation covered a wide range of advanced measurement techniques in aerodynamics, including 3D density measurement, PIV analysis, drag coefficient evaluations, turbulence visualization, and flow field quantification in various supersonic and hypersonic scenarios. Participants focused on methods like Schlieren visualization, glow discharge plasma, and spectroscopic measurements to study aerodynamic phenomena such as sonic flow, re-entry capsules, and free-flying objects. The discussions also delved into drag coefficient determination, pressure distribution measurements, and velocity fluctuation analysis in high-speed environments.

Background-Oriented Schlieren (BOS) Techniques (35 items，3.5%) slope=0.24%/yr

The discussions centered around enhancing spatial resolution in three-dimensional flow field measurements using background-oriented schlieren (BOS) method. Participants explored techniques like neural network-based super-resolution, adaptive optics, and shadowgrab video generation. They also delved into topics such as flow field visualization, shock wave measurement, and the transition from laser interferometry computed tomography to BOS-CT. The emphasis was on improving accuracy, resolution, and visualization in BOS applications, particularly in supersonic flows and vibration environments.

Viscoelastic Shock Wave Analysis (33 items，3.3%) slope=0.12%/yr

The consultation covered a wide range of topics related to shock wave phenomena, including molecular dynamics simulations, tissue damage studies, shock wave propagation in various materials, shock wave attenuation methods, and shock-induced phase transitions. The discussions delved into the effects of shock waves on lipid vesicles, biomimetic materials, rock materials, and viscoelastic media, as well as the use of shock waves for concrete destruction and material property evaluation. The participants explored diverse areas such as shock wave generation, bubble oscillation, crack-controlled fracture, and shock-induced luminescence, highlighting the multidisciplinary nature of shock wave research.

Detonation Engine Research and Development (30 items，3.0%) slope=-0.13%/yr

The studies also covered propellants like liquid ethanol, hydrogen, oxygen, methane, and dimethyl ether, as well as concepts like air-breathing rocket-switching engines and oblique detonation. The aim was to enhance performance, control thrust, and explore applications in space propulsion.

Hypervelocity Impact Damage Analysis in Glass Materials (30 items，3.0%) slope=-0.26%/yr

The consultation covered a wide range of topics related to hypervelocity impact and damage analysis, including crack propagation in glass materials, impact resistance evaluation in laminates, and damage behavior of various materials under high-speed impact. Participants delved into the influence of glass composition, mechanical properties, laminated layers, and bonded interfaces on damage progression. The discussions also touched on impact resistance in aircraft materials, fracture processes in different materials, and real-time visualization of damage formation processes during impact events. Molecular dynamics analysis was highlighted as a key method for studying damage in both polymer/metal composite structures and metallic materials.

Shock Wave Interaction Phenomena (30 items，3.0%) slope=-0.04%/yr

The consultation covered a wide range of topics related to shock wave interactions in supersonic flow, including characteristics of oblique shock wave interference, effects of viscosity, turbulence, and reflector conditions, as well as the impact of various factors on shock wave formations and reflections. Participants discussed the influence of different shapes, rise times, and maximum pressures on turbulent interactions, as well as the transition from weak to strong shock waves. Additionally, the study delved into the collision processes of supersonic jets and shock waves, unimolecular reactions behind shock waves, and the modulation of shock fronts by grid turbulence. The research also explored the interaction of flames, vortex rings, and flexible bodies with shock waves in various flow conditions.

Hydrogen-Oxygen Flame Dynamics (28 items，2.8%) slope=0.22%/yr

The research focused on areas such as flame detection, detonation wave propagation, cool flame observations, and autoignition characteristics, providing valuable insights into combustion processes and potential applications in engine design and safety measures. The diverse array of studies showcased a deep interest in understanding the complex dynamics of combustion and ignition in various fuel systems.

Plasma Flow Diagnostics and Measurement (26 items，2.6%) slope=-0.41%/yr

The focus was on characterizing plasma flows, evaluating projectile temperatures, and developing measurement probes for arc gas flows. The discussions also included topics like high-speed particle injection, electromagnetic force modeling, and heat flux measurements in ultra-high-speed gas flows.

Pressure-Sensitive Paint (PSP) for High-Speed Flow Visualization (24 items，2.4%) slope=-0.70%/yr

Participants highlighted the development and application of various high-speed and responsive paints for aerodynamic analysis, including temperature-sensitive paint for shock tube experiments, pressure-sensitive paint for surface pressure measurement, and anodized aluminum pressure-sensitive paint for sonic boom visualization. The focus was on enhancing measurement accuracy and speed in analyzing supersonic and high-speed flows, with considerations for factors like response times and preparation methods affecting paint performance. Additionally, there was an emphasis on utilizing these paints for gas flow analysis and evaluating properties of different coatings for pressure-sensitive paint.

Expansion Tube Flow Diagnostics (15 items，1.5%) slope=-0.17%/yr

Experimental Shock Wave Research Facilities (11 items，1.1%) slope=-0.09%/yr

Key research initiatives in Japan include the development of ballistic range and fluid measurement technology at Tokai University, establishment of a hypersonic wind tunnel at the University of Tokyo, and research on rotating detonation engines at Yokohama National University. Other notable projects involve high-speed projectile launchers at Ritsumeikan University and solid-state research using shooting guns at Kumamoto University. The tribute to Professor Toshitaka Fujiwara highlights his contributions to physics and his legacy of kindness and brilliance.
